## Methodology

### Step 1 — Data Loading and Merging

All 21 CSV files were loaded and merged into a single DataFrame. The anomaly-free file was assigned label `0` (normal) for all rows. The valve1 and valve2 files each contain an `anomaly` column with binary labels (`0` = normal, `1` = fault), which were used directly.

Files were sorted chronologically by timestamp before any further processing to preserve the time-series order.

### Step 2 — Class Distribution Analysis

After merging:
- **Normal rows:** 24,049 (75.4%)
- **Fault rows:** 7,826 (24.6%)
- **Imbalance ratio:** 3.07:1 (Normal:Fault)

A 3:1 ratio represents moderate class imbalance. This means a naive model that always predicts "normal" would achieve 75% accuracy — which is misleading. For this reason, accuracy alone is not a reliable metric and F1-score on the fault class is used as the primary evaluation metric throughout this work.

### Step 3 — Signal Quality and Separability Check

Each sensor was analysed to determine how well it separates normal from fault conditions. The mean value per sensor was computed for both classes and the absolute difference was compared against the overall standard deviation.

| Sensor | Normal Mean | Fault Mean | Difference | Separable? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Accelerometer1RMS | 0.0997 | 0.0274 | 0.0722 | YES |
| Accelerometer2RMS | 0.1295 | 0.0405 | 0.0890 | YES |
| Current | 1.6720 | 1.2940 | 0.3780 | NO |
| Pressure | 0.0815 | 0.0617 | 0.0199 | NO |
| Temperature | 77.5867 | 69.6546 | 7.9321 | YES |
| Thermocouple | 26.2689 | 24.8532 | 1.4157 | YES |
| Voltage | 229.7918 | 230.3114 | 0.5196 | NO |
| Volume Flow RateRMS | 68.5194 | 29.7573 | 38.7620 | YES |

**5 out of 8 sensors** show clear separation between normal and fault states. Notably, Volume Flow RateRMS shows the largest difference (38.76), which is expected — closing a valve directly restricts flow. No missing values or near-constant columns were found.

### Step 4 — Preprocessing Pipeline

#### 4.1 Missing Value Handling
Forward-fill followed by backward-fill was applied to handle any gaps in the time-series. No missing values were found in this dataset.

#### 4.2 Chronological Train/Test Split
The dataset was split **chronologically** — the first 80% of rows used for training and the last 20% for testing. This approach is critical for time-series data to prevent future readings from leaking into the training set, which would produce artificially inflated results.

#### 4.3 Normalisation
MinMaxScaler was applied to scale all sensor features to the `[0, 1]` range. The scaler was **fitted on the training set only** and then applied to both train and test sets — again to prevent data leakage.

#### 4.4 Sliding Window Construction
Raw time-series rows were converted into fixed-length windows for supervised classification. Each window captures a sequence of consecutive sensor readings:

- **Window size:** 30 timesteps (30 seconds at 1 Hz sampling rate)
- **Step size:** 5 (windows overlap, maximising training samples)
- **Label rule:** A window is labelled `1` (fault) if **any** row within it contains a fault, otherwise `0` (normal)

This approach is standard for fault detection with time-series sensor data and ensures the model learns patterns leading up to a fault, not just the moment of failure.

| Split | Windows | Normal | Fault |
|---|---|---|---|
| Train (before SMOTE) | 5,095 | 3,913 | 1,182 |
| Test | 1,270 | 770 | 500 |

#### 4.5 SMOTE Oversampling
Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique (SMOTE) was applied to the training windows to balance the class distribution. SMOTE generates synthetic fault samples by interpolating between existing fault examples rather than simply duplicating them.

| Split | Windows | Normal | Fault |
|---|---|---|---|
| Train (after SMOTE) | 7,826 | 3,913 | 3,913 |

SMOTE was applied **only to the training set** — the test set remains untouched to reflect real-world class distribution.

