## Models

Five supervised classification models were trained and evaluated, covering a range of complexity from simple linear baselines to ensemble methods.

### Logistic Regression
A linear model that learns a weighted combination of input features to separate classes. Used as the baseline — if more complex models do not significantly outperform this, it suggests the data is linearly separable. Configured with `class_weight="balanced"` as an additional safeguard against residual imbalance.

### Decision Tree
A tree-based model that recursively splits the feature space using if/else rules on individual sensor values. Interpretable and fast but can overfit. Configured with `class_weight="balanced"`.

### Random Forest
An ensemble of 100 decision trees, each trained on a random subset of features and data. The final prediction is determined by majority vote across all trees. Random Forest is robust to overfitting, handles noisy sensor data well, and performs strongly on tabular time-series problems.

### Support Vector Machine (SVM)
Finds the optimal hyperplane that maximises the margin between normal and fault classes in high-dimensional feature space. Uses an RBF (radial basis function) kernel to handle non-linear boundaries. Configured with `class_weight="balanced"`.

### K-Nearest Neighbours (KNN)
A distance-based model that classifies each window by looking at the 5 most similar windows in the training set and taking a majority vote. Simple but computationally expensive and sensitive to the scale of features — which is why normalisation was applied first.

