## Results

### Per-Model Performance

| Model | Accuracy | Precision | Recall | F1-Score |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Logistic Regression | 86.38% | 100.00% | 65.40% | 79.08% |
| Decision Tree | 76.77% | 67.17% | 80.20% | 73.11% |
| Random Forest | **92.52%** | **99.51%** | **81.40%** | **89.55%** |
| SVM | 80.39% | 98.83% | 50.80% | 67.11% |
| KNN | 48.74% | 40.64% | 65.60% | 50.19% |

### Confusion Matrix Summary

| Model | TN | FP | FN | TP |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Logistic Regression | 770 | 0 | 173 | 327 |
| Decision Tree | 574 | 196 | 99 | 401 |
| Random Forest | 768 | 2 | 93 | 407 |
| SVM | 767 | 3 | 246 | 254 |
| KNN | 291 | 479 | 172 | 328 |

- **TP (True Positive):** Fault correctly identified as fault
- **TN (True Negative):** Normal correctly identified as normal
- **FP (False Positive):** Normal incorrectly flagged as fault
- **FN (False Negative):** Fault missed — most critical error in maintenance

### Key Observations

- **Random Forest** is the clear best performer with 89.55% F1 and only 2 false positives and 93 missed faults out of 500 fault windows
- **Logistic Regression** achieved perfect precision (no false alarms) but missed 173 faults — too conservative for a safety-critical maintenance system
- **SVM** had very high precision but poor recall — same issue as Logistic Regression
- **Decision Tree** had the best recall (80.2%) among the weaker models but generated 196 false alarms
- **KNN** struggled significantly, producing 479 false positives — not suitable for this data structure

